## 2. Holiday Special - Putting Shifts Together

<b>(a)</b> The optimal solution to our main problem is composed of optimal solutions of smaller subproblems such as most consecutive chef for a smaller number of steps.

<b>(b)</b> Find the chef with the most consecutive chefs, choose them, repeat but for the remaining steps.

<b>(d)</b> O(nm) where n = num of chefs and m = num of steps

<b>(e)</b> Let ALG = {a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, ..., a<sub>j</sub>} be the solution generated by my algorithm and let OPT = {o<sub>1</sub>, o<sub>2</sub>, ..., o<sub>k</sub>} be an optimal solution to this problem where k < j. Let i be the first switch where a<sub>i</sub> is not equal to o<sub>i</sub>. By design of our greedy algorithm, we can produce a list with the least number of switches between the group of chefs up till j switches. We can therefore use the cut and paste method to cut out o<sub>i</sub> and paste in a<sub>i</sub>. We can replace o<sub>i</sub> with a<sub>i</sub> all the way up to k, which would make the optimal solution {a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, ..., etc} So the optimal solution can be replaced with our greedy algorithm at every step which means our algorithm is optimal.
